      Anti-ESG
   =20
 =20
If you are the chief executive officer of a public company, there are vario=
us environmental, social and governance things you could do. You could, lik=
e, switch your widget factory to use sustainably harvested natural widget m=
aterials instead of highly polluting fossil-fuel-derived widget materials o=
r whatever. This would cost you more money and reduce profit margins, but. =
But something. But what?=C2=A0=09=E2=80=9CBut it would be good for the plan=
et, and you live on the planet, and you want your grandchildren to have=E2=
=80=9D etc. is one form of argument but let=E2=80=99s rule it out. You are =
a fiduciary, you work for shareholders, you can only consider arguments abo=
ut shareholders=E2=80=99 interests. Your grandchildren=E2=80=99s interest i=
n a livable planet=C2=A0cannot outweigh your shareholders=E2=80=99 interest=
 in somewhat higher profit margins. (There are forms of =E2=80=9Cstakeholde=
r capitalism=E2=80=9D that reject this view,=C2=A0but they strike me as  so=
mewhat undertheorized. Of course in practice=C2=A0you can expect CEOs not t=
o be profit-maximizing psychopaths, but as a matter of constructing argumen=
ts about corporate finance, a CEO=E2=80=99s personal, societal and politica=
l=C2=A0preferences seem out of bounds compared to=C2=A0stuff about sharehol=
ders.)=09=E2=80=9CBut it would be good for the planet, and=C2=A0your shareh=
olders=C2=A0live on the planet, and you want=C2=A0their=C2=A0grandchildren =
to have a nice planet.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0This strikes me as a pretty good argum=
ent? It is a somewhat strange corporate finance argument, but it is a thing=
 that I  think about a lot around here. Shouldn=E2=80=99t companies do what=
 is in the actual interests of shareholders, what the shareholders=C2=A0act=
ually=C2=A0want, rather than robotically maximize profits? This can play ou=
t in various ways =E2=80=94=C2=A0companies with lots of meme-driven retail =
shareholders can   give their shareholders memes, companies with lots of un=
ion-pension-fund shareholders can treat their unionized workers well, compa=
nies with lots of large diversified shareholders can try to   maximize econ=
omy-wide profits rather than their own profits, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but cer=
tainly one way for it to play out might be =E2=80=9Ccompanies with sharehol=
ders who are humans living on Earth can try to make Earth livable.=E2=80=9D=
 One important reason that this is a strange corporate finance argument is =
that shareholders have heterogeneous desires. Everyone wants more money, or=
 anyway it is convenient to assume that they do, but they might want differ=
ent kinds of ESG stuff in different mixtures.=C2=A0(For instance, much ESG =
stuff is politically controversial, and your left-wing shareholders might w=
ant the opposite thing from your right-wing shareholders.) =E2=80=9CWe will=
 maximize the long-term happiness and life satisfaction of our shareholders=
 and their families=E2=80=9D is probably a=C2=A0better=C2=A0goal than =E2=
=80=9Cwe will maximize this year=E2=80=99s profit,=E2=80=9D but it is certa=
inly a much=C2=A0harder=C2=A0goal to quantify and measure and achieve.=09=
=E2=80=9CBut in the long run society will ban highly polluting fossil-fuel-=
derived widget materials, and companies that pollute will suffer legal and =
reputational consequences,=C2=A0so doing environmentally friendly things no=
w might lead to lower short-term profits as you retool the widget factory b=
ut will lead to higher long-term profits=C2=A0as your business is more sust=
ainable.=E2=80=9D This is I think the   most   standard   form of   ESG arg=
ument. It uses ESG as a tool to get to profit maximization; you can feel go=
od about yourself both as a person on Earth and also as a fiduciary value-m=
aximizer. But this argument has some empirical content, and it can be true =
for some decisions and false for others. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re going to sw=
itch to recyclable packaging for our widgets at a cost of $0.02 per widget =
because our government relations team expects tough restrictions on non-rec=
yclable packaging to be enacted in multiple jurisdictions in the next six m=
onths=E2=80=9D is a version of this that sounds plausible, while =E2=80=9Cw=
e are going to abandon=C2=A0our factories and let them return to nature bec=
ause in the long run society will reject striving for material goods=E2=80=
=9D seems less likely to maximize shareholder value. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re=
 going to get out of the coal business because it seems like a long-run los=
er=E2=80=9D is perhaps a good argument for a diversified commodities compan=
y that can sell its coal mines at a high price today and focus on businesse=
s with better long-term prospects, but a less good (financial) argument for=
 a pure-play coal miner.=C2=A0=09=E2=80=9CBut your shareholders=C2=A0want=
=C2=A0you to do good ESG things, either because they=C2=A0believe Argument =
2 (they are human, want their grandchildren to have nice things, etc.),=C2=
=A0or=C2=A0because they correctly believe Argument 3 (you will have higher =
sustainable long-term profits),=C2=A0or=C2=A0because they incorrectly belie=
ve Argument 3 but that=E2=80=99s their problem, and you can maximize the lo=
ng-term value of your company by=C2=A0giving shareholders what they want ev=
en if it does not maximize the net present value of your projects, because =
(1) if shareholders like you they will buy stock and you will have access t=
o cheap capital that you can use to do good business things and create fund=
amental value for shareholders and/or (2) if shareholders like you they wil=
l buy stock and your stock price will go up, which is shareholder value all=
 by itself.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Something like that? =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m just he=
re to maximize my stock price,=E2=80=9D you might say, =E2=80=9Cand right n=
ow stock prices go up when companies do ESG things, so I=E2=80=99m gonna do=
 ESG things, and I don=E2=80=99t think it requires more corporate finance a=
nalysis than that.=E2=80=9D As the CEO, you do whatever makes the stock go =
up, because markets are efficient and the stock price is better at this tha=
n you are. I sort of like this argument too.[1] I assume most CEOs would ob=
ject to this, and I see their point, but there is something pleasing about =
the simplicity here.Anyway here=E2=80=99s a guy:Unilever has =E2=80=9Clost =
the plot=E2=80=9D and its management prizes displaying its sustainability c=
redentials at the expense of running the business, according to influential=
 fund manager Terry Smith.The founder of Fundsmith, a top-10 shareholder in=
 Unilever whose stellar long-term record has helped him amass a large retai=
l following, used his annual letter to investors on Tuesday to hit out at t=
he global consumer goods group.The maker of Dove soap, Hellmann=E2=80=99s m=
ayonnaise and Magnum ice cream has set out ambitious climate and social tar=
gets and is trying to prove that sustainable business does drive superior f=
inancial performance.Smith, a veteran stockpicker who runs the =C2=A328.9bn=
 flagship Fundsmith Equity Fund, wrote: =E2=80=9CUnilever seems to be labou=
ring under the weight of a management which is obsessed with publicly displ=
aying sustainability credentials at the expense of focusing on the fundamen=
tals of the business.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0He said that while =E2=80=9Cthe most ob=
vious manifestation of this is the public spat it has become embroiled in o=
ver the refusal to supply Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s ice cream in the West Bank=
=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89there are far more ludicrous example=
s which illustrate the problem=E2=80=9D.Smith added: =E2=80=9CA company whi=
ch feels it has to define the purpose of Hellmann=E2=80=99s mayonnaise has =
in our view clearly lost the plot. The Hellmann=E2=80=99s brand has existed=
 since 1913 so we would guess that by now consumers have figured out its pu=
rpose (spoiler alert =E2=80=94 salads and sandwiches).=E2=80=9DThe high-pro=
file  cases of this sort of thing usually are  at energy companies, where s=
hareholders have deep disagreements about both the morality and the economi=
cs of drilling a lot of oil now versus investing a lot in green technology.=
 Sometimes the solution proposed there is to  split up the company into a g=
reen company that will appeal to ESG-focused investors, and a legacy-coal-a=
nd-oil company that will appeal to cash-flow-focused investors.That seems l=
ess likely to work here.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t think Unilever will separate =
out its mission-driven mayo from its cynical opportunistic mayo. It=E2=80=
=99s really just=C2=A0the one mayo.=C2=A0The question is whether you will m=
ake the mayo in a way that appeals to your ESG-driven investors or one that=
 doesn=E2=80=99t. One way to answer that question is to inquire into the fi=
nancial logic and decide, to the satisfaction of the executives and the boa=
rd and the shareholders, whether =E2=80=9Csustainable business does drive s=
uperior financial performance.=E2=80=9D Another way to answer that question=
 is to say =E2=80=9Cwell there sure are a lot of investors who own a lot of=
 our shares and who keep asking us to do ESG stuff, and then there=E2=80=99=
s one guy writing a mean letter saying that we shouldn=E2=80=99t, so let=E2=
=80=99s do whatever minimizes the total quantity of shareholder complaining=
.=E2=80=9D Minimizing shareholder complaining seems like a valid corporate =
finance goal? My sense is that right now the weight of shareholder energy i=
s on the pro-ESG side, but I guess if you want to change that you have to s=
tart with one mean letter.
