   =20
      Who controls a company?=C2=A0
   =20
 =20
It is sort of a miracle that hostile takeovers and proxy fights can work. Y=
ou=E2=80=99ve got a company. The company is a collection of people who all =
go to the same building=C2=A0and do things together. The company is run by =
a chief executive officer and a board of directors, who tend to be pretty c=
hummy with each other. The CEO hires the other executives, who hire the oth=
er employees. They all work with each other and tend to get along: They wer=
e hired by people who thought they=E2=80=99d fit in with the group, and if =
they don=E2=80=99t fit in they can be fired. As in any group there will be =
some infighting and dysfunction but it is basically a group of people who h=
ave come together for a common purpose and spend a lot of time together wor=
king toward that purpose.And then one day some stranger shows up and says =
=E2=80=9CI have bought 4% of your company and I want you to do different th=
ings.=E2=80=9D And the board and the CEO and the executives and the employe=
es are like =E2=80=9Cthanks but no=E2=80=9D and go about their business. An=
d then the stranger goes to some other shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0some oth=
er strangers, as far as the employees are concerned=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 convinces them of the rightness of her vision, which is not shared by the =
board or CEO or executives or employees who are actually doing the work, an=
d she comes back and says =E2=80=9CI have bought your company and control i=
t now, the board is fired, the CEO is fired, the rest of you employees can =
stay but you have to do what I say now.=E2=80=9D[2] And it works! The execu=
tives and employees are like =E2=80=9Cokay I guess you=E2=80=99re the boss.=
=E2=80=9D The CEO and the directors just leave and do something else. The c=
ustomers and suppliers who worked with the company continue working with th=
e company, and it=E2=80=99s the same company.=C2=A0It is no longer owned by=
 the same people or run by the same people, but there is continuity of the =
corporate entity, and that fictitious entity actually matters in the real w=
orld.=C2=A0You could imagine it=C2=A0not=C2=A0working. You could imagine th=
e CEO barricading himself in his office and saying =E2=80=9Cwho put you in =
charge? =E2=80=98Shareholders=E2=80=99? Sounds fake.=E2=80=9D You could ima=
gine=C2=A0the CEO sitting down at his computer and using his unchanged pass=
word to type an email to all staff saying =E2=80=9Cignore these weirdos say=
ing that they run the company, I run the company, keep doing your jobs.=E2=
=80=9D You could imagine the employees saying =E2=80=9Cyou know, I like wor=
king for my boss, and we share a sense of mission and a long history togeth=
er, and these new people seem to want strange and different things, I guess=
 I=C2=A0will=C2=A0ignore them and keep listening to the CEO.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
A company is built around a set of fairly thick social ties, and also aroun=
d knowing the computer passwords and having keycards that work on the doors=
 and stuff like that. And then it is connected to its shareholders by rathe=
r thin social ties, and when the shareholders decide to come in and mess wi=
th the internal workings it is strange that they=C2=A0can.I mean, it is not=
=C2=A0that=C2=A0strange. It is straightforward=C2=A0textbook stuff. The way=
 that corporate law works most places is that the shareholders more or less=
 own the company, and a majority of them can get together and more or less =
fire the board and the executives if they=E2=80=99re unhappy with them, and=
 the people appointed to run the company by the shareholders have the legal=
 right to run the company, and if you stand in their way =E2=80=94=C2=A0if =
you barricade yourself in your office when the new shareholder-appointed CE=
O comes to kick you out =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the shareholders can go to cour=
t and get a court order telling you to clear out and call the police to enf=
orce it. And in most places where hostile takeovers happen this is widely u=
nderstood stuff, and there is a high degree of confidence that the courts a=
nd the police=C2=A0will=C2=A0enforce it, so it would be=C2=A0foolish and se=
lf-destructive for the CEO to barricade himself in his office. And even if =
the employees like the old CEO and the old mission and find the new owners =
uncongenial, they just accept the system; they might grumble or even=C2=A0q=
uit en masse but they won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0ignore=C2=A0the takeover.This is h=
owever a very U.S.-centric perspective and it=E2=80=99s not obvious that ev=
ery company everywhere would work this way. It would be funny if you ran a =
proxy fight at a foreign company and got the shareholders to agree with you=
 and ousted the board and installed a new chief executive officer and that =
CEO showed up at his first day of work and the old CEO was like =E2=80=9Cwh=
o put you in charge? =E2=80=98Shareholders=E2=80=99?=C2=A0Sounds fake.=E2=
=80=9D And then you=E2=80=99d have to navigate a court system with less iro=
nclad precedent for all of this stuff, and maybe in the end it would all wo=
rk out, but it is not automatic and assumed the way it is in the U.S.There=
=E2=80=99s a company called Nam Tai Property Inc. Nam Tai is incorporated i=
n the British Virgin Islands and listed on the New York Stock Exchange, so =
it is in some rough sense a U.S. public company. (Here is its annual report=
 for 2020, filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.) But it =
is headquartered in Shenzhen, its business consists of developing and opera=
ting real estate in China, its assets are in China and it mainly operates t=
hrough Chinese subsidiaries. Under Virgin Islands corporate law and U.S. se=
curities law, you can go ahead and have a proxy fight. But then what?Last y=
ear, a small hedge fund called IsZo Capital Management LP[3] =E2=80=9Cpreva=
iled in a 16-month battle to wrest control of the New York-listed Chinese d=
eveloper.=E2=80=9D Sort of! Nam Tai=E2=80=99s largest shareholder is anothe=
r Chinese property developer, Kaisa Group Holdings Ltd., and IsZo led Nam T=
ai=E2=80=99s=C2=A0other=C2=A0shareholders in a revolt against the company=
=E2=80=99s Kaisa-connected board and management. This was a complicated fig=
ht:=C2=A0Before a shareholders=E2=80=99 meeting could be convened to consid=
er the merits of the IsZo proposal, Nam Tai executed a transaction that dra=
matically strengthened Kaisa=E2=80=99s hand. The technology park developer =
sold $170 million of stock, mostly to its controlling shareholder, raising =
Kaisa=E2=80=99s stake to 43.9% from 23.9%.But IsZo went to court (in the Vi=
rgin Islands) and a judge voided the transaction. =E2=80=9CAfter appeals, t=
he shareholders=E2=80=99 meeting finally went ahead [in November]. All IsZo=
=E2=80=99s slate of six candidates were elected, with support from more tha=
n 94% of holders unaffiliated with Kaisa.=E2=80=9DHaving won at the shareho=
lder meeting, IsZo captured certain key strategic positions. For instance: =
Nam Tai=E2=80=99s passwords for the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission=
=E2=80=99s Edgar filing system. The board elected by the shareholders seems=
 to control the filings. Here=E2=80=99s the press release that Nam Tai file=
d on Dec. 3, after the shareholder meeting, announcing the results of the m=
eeting=C2=A0and the makeup of the new board. Normal stuff.Controlling the b=
oard of directors of the U.S.-listed, Virgin Islands-incorporated public co=
mpany is not, however, quite the same thing as controlling the operations o=
f a Chinese property developer. Here is an open letter to shareholders that=
 Nam Tai filed today:Dear Shareholders,We want to update you on our path to=
 securing total on-shore control of Nam Tai Property Inc. (=E2=80=9CNam Tai=
=E2=80=9D or the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) and its assets. In recent weeks=
, Jiabiao Wang, whom we believe to be a longtime ally of Kaisa Group Holdin=
gs Limited (collectively with its affiliates, =E2=80=9CKaisa Group=E2=80=9D=
) and whom the reconstituted Board of Directors (the =E2=80=9CBoard=E2=80=
=9D) has terminated from any role at Nam Tai, has obstructed an orderly han=
dover of business assets in mainland China. ...In direct contravention of t=
he elected Board=E2=80=99s decisions and in what appears to be a flagrant v=
iolation of the law, Mr. Wang =E2=80=93 evidently a long-time ally of Kaisa=
 Group =E2=80=93 is refusing to acknowledge his formal termination and faci=
litate an orderly handover of the on-shore business despite multiple visits=
 and demands by the Board=E2=80=99s recently-appointed legal representative=
 and the new management of the Company. Mr. Wang is currently preventing th=
e new Board from accessing the Company=E2=80=99s and its subsidiaries=E2=80=
=99 business licenses, corporate seals (also known as chops) and several ba=
nk accounts. We believe Mr. Wang and Kaisa Group are also responsible for t=
he following:Issuing false and misleading communications to local stakehold=
ers in China via the Company=E2=80=99s website and other channels;Preventin=
g the Board from communicating with the Company=E2=80=99s valued employees =
in China;Refusing to provide access to the Company=E2=80=99s books and reco=
rds and systems,Purportedly engaging =E2=80=93 without authorization =E2=80=
=93 a Chinese law firm on behalf of the Company to assist with their effort=
s in obstructing the Board=E2=80=99s newly-appointed legal representative a=
nd management from accessing the Company, and;Threatening =E2=80=93 without=
 any basis =E2=80=93 legal action against the Board=E2=80=99s recently-appo=
inted legal representative for trying to fulfill the Board=E2=80=99s assign=
ments and instructions.While we suspect Mr.=C2=A0Wang is authorizing unsanc=
tioned compensation for himself and spending corporate funds on outside law=
yers, he has no real authority to represent the Company, allocate its funds=
 or commit to any kind of transaction with vendors and third parties. Any a=
ttempts by Mr.=C2=A0Wang to dispose of or transfer corporate assets are una=
uthorized and will not be recognized by the elected Board. The Board and it=
s appointees have already notified third parties with whom Mr.=C2=A0Wang ha=
s interacted that any commitments by Mr.=C2=A0Wang are unauthorized and wil=
l not be honored, and the Board has publicized the fact that Mr.=C2=A0Wang =
has been terminated and therefore has no authority to act on behalf of any =
Nam Tai entity.So the old CEO has barricaded himself in the office, apparen=
tly retains the loyalty of the staff (or at least their email addresses), a=
nd still has the corporate chops, the bank-account information and the pass=
words to the website (though not to Edgar). And it seems like he is telling=
 =E2=80=9Cvendors and third parties=E2=80=9D that he=E2=80=99s still the CE=
O, and the newly elected board is telling them that he isn=E2=80=99t. Who s=
hould they believe? The new board seems to have offshore control =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it is legally in charge as far as the U.S. and the Virgin Islands are=
 concerned, it makes the U.S. securities filings, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, =
for a Chinese property company, onshore control is really=C2=A0what you wan=
t.[4]Anyway the shareholders=C2=A0have very much called the cops =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe Board has responded by actively engaging with local gove=
rnment officials to address Mr. Wang and Kaisa Group=E2=80=99s apparent int=
erference and uphold social stability=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and, you know=
, we=E2=80=99ll see!
