<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Who controls a company?=C2=A0</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is sort of a miracle that hostile t=
akeovers and proxy fights can work. You=E2=80=99ve got a company. The compa=
ny is a collection of people who all go to the same building=C2=A0and do th=
ings together. The company is run by a chief executive officer and a board =
of directors, who tend to be pretty chummy with each other. The CEO hires t=
he other executives, who hire the other employees. They all work with each =
other and tend to get along: They were hired by people who thought they=E2=
=80=99d fit in with the group, and if they don=E2=80=99t fit in they can be=
 fired. As in any group there will be some infighting and dysfunction but i=
t is basically a group of people who have come together for a common purpos=
e and spend a lot of time together working toward that purpose.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then one day some stranger shows up and says =E2=
=80=9CI have bought 4% of your company and I want you to do different thing=
s.=E2=80=9D And the board and the CEO and the executives and the employees =
are like =E2=80=9Cthanks but no=E2=80=9D and go about their business. And t=
hen the stranger goes to some other shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0some other =
strangers, as far as the employees are concerned=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and co=
nvinces them of the rightness of her vision, which is not shared by the boa=
rd or CEO or executives or employees who are actually doing the work, and s=
he comes back and says =E2=80=9CI have bought your company and control it n=
ow, the board is fired, the CEO is fired, the rest of you employees can sta=
y but you have to do what I say now.=E2=80=9D[2] And it works! The executiv=
es and employees are like =E2=80=9Cokay I guess you=E2=80=99re the boss.=E2=
=80=9D The CEO and the directors just leave and do something else. The cust=
omers and suppliers who worked with the company continue working with the c=
ompany, and it=E2=80=99s the same company.=C2=A0It is no longer owned by th=
e same people or run by the same people, but there is continuity of the cor=
porate entity, and that fictitious entity actually matters in the real worl=
d.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine it=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>working. You could imagine the CEO barricading himself in his of=
fice and saying =E2=80=9Cwho put you in charge? =E2=80=98Shareholders=E2=80=
=99? Sounds fake.=E2=80=9D You could imagine=C2=A0the CEO sitting down at h=
is computer and using his unchanged password to type an email to all staff =
saying =E2=80=9Cignore these weirdos saying that they run the company, I ru=
n the company, keep doing your jobs.=E2=80=9D You could imagine the employe=
es saying =E2=80=9Cyou know, I like working for my boss, and we share a sen=
se of mission and a long history together, and these new people seem to wan=
t strange and different things, I guess I=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>ignore th=
em and keep listening to the CEO.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">A company is built around a set of fairly thick social ties, and also=
 around knowing the computer passwords and having keycards that work on the=
 doors and stuff like that. And then it is connected to its shareholders by=
 rather thin social ties, and when the shareholders decide to come in and m=
ess with the internal workings it is strange that they=C2=A0<em>can</em>.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, it is not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>st=
range. It is straightforward=C2=A0textbook stuff. The way that corporate la=
w works most places is that the shareholders more or less own the company, =
and a majority of them can get together and more or less fire the board and=
 the executives if they=E2=80=99re unhappy with them, and the people appoin=
ted to run the company by the shareholders have the legal right to run the =
company, and if you stand in their way =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you barricade your=
self in your office when the new shareholder-appointed CEO comes to kick yo=
u out =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the shareholders can go to court and get a court =
order telling you to clear out and call the police to enforce it. And in mo=
st places where hostile takeovers happen this is widely understood stuff, a=
nd there is a high degree of confidence that the courts and the police=C2=
=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>enforce it, so it would be=C2=A0foolish and self-dest=
ructive for the CEO to barricade himself in his office. And even if the emp=
loyees like the old CEO and the old mission and find the new owners unconge=
nial, they just accept the system; they might grumble or even=C2=A0quit en =
masse but they won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>ignore=C2=A0</em>the takeover.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is however a very U.S.-centric perspective a=
nd it=E2=80=99s not obvious that every company everywhere would work this w=
ay. It would be funny if you ran a proxy fight at a foreign company and got=
 the shareholders to agree with you and ousted the board and installed a ne=
w chief executive officer and that CEO showed up at his first day of work a=
nd the old CEO was like =E2=80=9Cwho put you in charge? =E2=80=98Shareholde=
rs=E2=80=99?=C2=A0Sounds fake.=E2=80=9D And then you=E2=80=99d have to navi=
gate a court system with less ironclad precedent for all of this stuff, and=
 maybe in the end it would all work out, but it is not automatic and assume=
d the way it is in the U.S.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s=
 a company called Nam Tai Property Inc. Nam Tai is incorporated in the Brit=
ish Virgin Islands and listed on the New York Stock Exchange, so it is in s=
ome rough sense a U.S. public company. (Here is its <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26344380.297645/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvd=
i9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODI5MzY1LzAwMDE1NjQ1OTAyMTAxODc2NS9u=
dHAtMjBmXzIwMjAxMjMxLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb6f6bef5" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">annua=
l report for 2020</a>, filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commissi=
on.) But it is headquartered in Shenzhen, its business consists of developi=
ng and operating real estate in China, its assets are in China and it mainl=
y operates through Chinese subsidiaries. Under Virgin Islands corporate law=
 and U.S. securities law, you can go ahead and have a proxy fight. But then=
 what?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year, a small hedge fund called=
 IsZo Capital Management LP[3] =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/26344380.297645/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3RvbnBvc3QuY=
29tL2J1c2luZXNzL3RoZS1oZWRnZS1mdW5kLXRoYXQtdG9vay1vbi1rYWlzYS1hbmQtd29uLzIw=
MjEvMTIvMDkvOGQxNzkyZWMtNTk0NC0xMWVjLTgzOTYtNTU1MmJlZjU1YzNjX3N0b3J5Lmh0bWw=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB43dbc63a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">prevailed in a 16-month battle<=
/a> to wrest control of the New York-listed Chinese developer.=E2=80=9D Sor=
t of! Nam Tai=E2=80=99s largest shareholder is another Chinese property dev=
eloper, Kaisa Group Holdings Ltd., and IsZo led Nam Tai=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>=
other=C2=A0</em>shareholders in a revolt against the company=E2=80=99s Kais=
a-connected board and management. This was a complicated fight:=C2=A0</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Before a shareholders=E2=80=99 meeti=
ng could be convened to consider the merits of the IsZo proposal, Nam Tai e=
xecuted a transaction that dramatically strengthened Kaisa=E2=80=99s hand. =
The technology park developer sold $170 million of stock, mostly to its con=
trolling shareholder, raising Kaisa=E2=80=99s stake to 43.9% from 23.9%.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But IsZo went to court (in the V=
irgin Islands) and a judge voided the transaction. =E2=80=9CAfter appeals, =
the shareholders=E2=80=99 meeting finally went ahead [in November]. All IsZ=
o=E2=80=99s slate of six candidates were elected, with support from more th=
an 94% of holders unaffiliated with Kaisa.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Having won at the shareholder meeting, IsZo captured certain key s=
trategic positions. For instance: Nam Tai=E2=80=99s passwords for the U.S. =
Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s Edgar filing system. The board=
 elected by the shareholders seems to control the filings. Here=E2=80=99s <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26344380.297645/aHR=
