takeholders in China via the Company=E2=80=99s website and other channels;<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Preventing the Board from communicating wit=
h the Company=E2=80=99s valued employees in China;</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Refusing to provide access to the Company=E2=80=99s books and recor=
ds and systems,</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purportedly engaging =E2=80=
=93 without authorization =E2=80=93 a Chinese law firm on behalf of the Com=
pany to assist with their efforts in obstructing the Board=E2=80=99s newly-=
appointed legal representative and management from accessing the Company, a=
nd;</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Threatening =E2=80=93 without any basis=
 =E2=80=93 legal action against the Board=E2=80=99s recently-appointed lega=
l representative for trying to fulfill the Board=E2=80=99s assignments and =
instructions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While we suspect Mr.=C2=A0Wan=
g is authorizing unsanctioned compensation for himself and spending corpora=
te funds on outside lawyers, he has no real authority to represent the Comp=
any, allocate its funds or commit to any kind of transaction with vendors a=
nd third parties. Any attempts by Mr.=C2=A0Wang to dispose of or transfer c=
orporate assets are unauthorized and will not be recognized by the elected =
Board. The Board and its appointees have already notified third parties wit=
h whom Mr.=C2=A0Wang has interacted that any commitments by Mr.=C2=A0Wang a=
re unauthorized and will not be honored, and the Board has publicized the f=
act that Mr.=C2=A0Wang has been terminated and therefore has no authority t=
o act on behalf of any Nam Tai entity.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">So the old CEO has barricaded himself in the office, apparently re=
tains the loyalty of the staff (or at least their email addresses), and sti=
ll has the corporate chops, the bank-account information and the passwords =
to the website (though not to Edgar). And it seems like he is telling =E2=
=80=9Cvendors and third parties=E2=80=9D that he=E2=80=99s still the CEO, a=
nd the newly elected board is telling them that he isn=E2=80=99t. Who shoul=
d they believe? The new board seems to have offshore control =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it is legally in charge as far as the U.S. and the Virgin Islands are co=
ncerned, it makes the U.S. securities filings, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, for=
 a Chinese property company, onshore control is really=C2=A0what you want.[=
